4","1318":"1318","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1291–":"about 1291–Deceased","1291–Male":"1291–Deceased","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1264–Male":"1264–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1291":"about 1291","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1318":"1318","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sandes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Sands  .","Galician: habitational name from any of various places so named in Galicia (Spain). Compare   Sandez  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sands","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>sandes</i> ‘sands’, for someone who lived at or near a sandy place, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Sands in Carlisle (Cumberland) or Sands Cottages in West Hoathly (Sussex). See   Sand  , of which <i>Sands</i> may sometimes be a plural form or a variant, with excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare also   Sandes   and   Sandys  .","History: Comfort Sands, a revolutionary patriot born in 1748 at what is now Sands’ Point, Long Island, NY, was descended from James Sand(y)s (1622–95), who emigrated from Reading, Berkshire, England, to Plymouth, MA, and followed Anne Hutchinson to Westchester County, NY, and subsequently RI. In 1661 he settled on Block Island, RI."]},{"name":"Sandez","meanings":["Galician: variant of   Sandes  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":24,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":37,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":46,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Sandes was born about 1291, in Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England as the son of Richard del Sandes. He had at least 2 sons. He died in Carlisle, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1291–":"umbes 1291–Surnud","1291–Male":"1291–Surnud","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1291":"umbes 1291","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1318":"1318","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"about 1291–":"noin 1291–Kuollut","1291–Male":"1291–Kuollut","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1264–Male":"1264–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1291":"noin 1291","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1318":"1318","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England"},"fr":{"about 1291–":"environ 1291–Décédé","1291–Male":"1291–Décédé","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1264–Male":"1264–Décédé","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1291":"environ 1291","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1318":"1318","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cu